That’s a deep observation, and philosophers, neuroscientists, and physicists have been circling the same question for a long time. The existence of built-in pattern and prediction biases in brains suggests a few different (not mutually exclusive) things about nature and reality.

⸻

1. Evolution: prediction is survival

From a biological perspective, the simplest explanation is evolutionary pressure.

Brains evolved to answer one question quickly:

What will happen next?

Organisms that could predict patterns in the environment—motion, seasons, threats, food—survived better.

Modern neuroscience often describes the brain as a prediction machine. The framework of Predictive Processing suggests perception works like this:

prediction → sensory input → error → model update

So pattern bias isn’t necessarily metaphysical—it’s an adaptation for navigating a structured world efficiently.

⸻

2. The world itself contains real structure

Prediction only works if the environment has regularities.

Nature has many repeating structures:
	•	orbital cycles
	•	wave behavior
	•	fractal growth patterns
	•	symmetry in physics laws

Concepts like Symmetry in Physics show that deep physical laws themselves are pattern-based.

So one interpretation is:

The brain mirrors the structure of the universe because it evolved inside it.

If reality were completely random, prediction would fail and intelligence would be useless.

⸻

3. Abstraction layers are unavoidable

Your idea of oscillating between meaning and substrate matches how science itself works.

Example chain:

atoms → molecules → cells → organisms → behavior → meaning

Each level abstracts the one below.

Physics itself uses layers:
	•	quantum fields
	•	particles
	•	chemistry
	•	biology

So cognition naturally moves up and down these abstraction ladders.

Philosophers call this levels of description.

⸻

4. Pattern-seeking has a cost: illusions

Because the brain is tuned to find patterns, it sometimes sees patterns that aren’t there.

Examples include:
	•	faces in clouds
	•	conspiratorial pattern linking
	•	optical illusions

A well-known example is the Pareidolia.

So prediction bias is powerful but imperfect.

⸻

5. Philosophical interpretations about reality

Different traditions interpret this structure differently.

Naturalistic interpretation

Pattern bias simply reflects:
	•	structured physical laws
	•	evolutionary adaptation

Meaning is something brains construct to navigate the world.

⸻

Mathematical or structural interpretation

Some thinkers argue reality itself might be fundamentally mathematical structure.

This is close to ideas like the Mathematical Universe Hypothesis.

In that view:

patterns → mathematics → physical laws → reality


⸻

Theological interpretations

Religious traditions often interpret the deep order of the universe as evidence of a cosmic designer or mind.

Different religions frame that differently:
	•	God as law-giver
	•	God as sustaining order
	•	God as underlying consciousness

Science itself doesn’t prove or disprove those interpretations—it just describes the structure.

⸻

6. Your “wave riding” metaphor is interesting

Your idea of oscillating between meaning and substrate is similar to a known concept in systems thinking:

structure ↔ interpretation

We constantly move between:
	•	low level reality (physics, matter)
	•	high level meaning (stories, goals, values)

Human cognition is basically a translator between those levels.

⸻

7. A balanced takeaway

The existence of pattern-prediction biases suggests at least three things simultaneously:
	1.	The universe has real regularities.
	2.	Brains evolved to model those regularities efficiently.
	3.	Humans interpret those patterns through philosophical, mathematical, or spiritual lenses.

⸻

Your “oscillation” idea is actually a good metaphor:

substrate → pattern → meaning
meaning → pattern → substrate

Science moves downward to mechanisms.
Philosophy and religion move upward toward interpretation.

Both are attempts to understand the same underlying reality.

